		<title>Twenty Raises $100M, Reaches $1 Billion Valuation</title>
		<link>https://ventureburn.com/twenty-raises-100m-reaches-1-billion-valuation/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Ekemini]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Wed, 17 Jun 2026 19:41:39 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[News]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Venture Capital]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://ventureburn.com/?p=202892</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Twenty has officially closed a $100 million Series B funding round. The strategic investment values the Arlington-based firm at $1 billion, minting it as a rare &#8220;deep-tech&#8221; unicorn and signalling</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/twenty-raises-100m-reaches-1-billion-valuation/" data-wpel-link="internal">Twenty Raises $100M, Reaches $1 Billion Valuation</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Twenty has officially closed a $100 million Series B </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/deepseek-raises-7-4b-at-50b-in-founder-led-deal/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">funding </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">round. The strategic investment values the Arlington-based firm at $1 billion, minting it as a rare &#8220;deep-tech&#8221; unicorn and signalling an aggressive institutional bet on the weaponisation of artificial intelligence within international cyber conflicts.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The round was led by tech investment heavyweight </span><a href="https://www.accel.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">Accel</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">, with active participation from a highly strategic syndicate of dual-use and defence-focused capital pools, including Point72 Ventures, Caffeinated Capital, and Friends &amp; Family Capital. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">This injection of capital brings Twenty’s total funding to $138 million since its inception less than two years ago, following a heavily discussed $38 million Series A round that featured participation from In-Q-Tel, the venture arm of the U.S. Intelligence Community.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Selling the Sword: Industrializing Offensive Cyber Operations</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Historically, the multi-billion-dollar cybersecurity startup ecosystem has focused almost exclusively on building defensive walls. Thousands of vendors sell digital shields designed to patch vulnerabilities, monitor endpoints, and detect network intrusions. Twenty has achieved its billion-dollar valuation by deliberately doing the exact opposite: it builds the sword.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Founded in 2024 by Chief Executive Officer Joe Lin alongside a team composed heavily of elite veterans from U.S. Cyber Command and the National Security Agency (NSA), Twenty is openly dedicated to industrialising machine-speed offensive cyber weapons. Instead of defending enterprise networks, the startup manufactures end-to-end, AI-enabled software frameworks designed to actively penetrate, disrupt, and neutralise adversarial digital infrastructure before those foreign actors can strike American targets.</span></p>
<div id="attachment_202918" style="width: 410px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-202918" class="wp-image-202918" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Twenty.jpeg" alt="Twenty" width="400" height="400" /><p id="caption-attachment-202918" class="wp-caption-text">Source: Twenty</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">&#8220;America is under sustained cyber attack, and our adversaries have learned correctly that those attacks rarely carry consequences,&#8221; said Joe Lin, co-founder and CEO of Twenty, in a statement accompanying the announcement. &#8220;Twenty exists to change that reality. We are building the industrial base for American cyber power.&#8221;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/deepseek-raises-7-4b-at-50b-in-founder-led-deal/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">DeepSeek Raises $7.4B at $50B+ in Founder-Led Deal</span></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Human-in-the-Loop AI for the Digital Frontline</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">At the technical core of Twenty’s platform is an autonomous tactical operating system that leverages advanced AI to map, target, and exploit adversary networks at a scale and speed that human operators cannot match manually. In modern cyber warfare, the time window to exploit a known vulnerability or counter an active state-sponsored intrusion is often measured in seconds, making legacy manual exploitation workflows obsolete.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">However, recognising the severe geopolitical risks associated with autonomous digital weapons, Twenty&#8217;s engineering framework emphasises a strict &#8220;human-in-the-loop&#8221; philosophy. The platform pairs high-speed machine automation with continuous algorithmic evaluation, rigorous mission alignment filters, and human-controlled deployment mechanisms. This ensures that legal, tactical, and strategic human judgement remains the final authorising factor before any offensive payload is launched into cyberspace.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The platform is not a conceptual prototype. Twenty confirmed it already commands multiple highly classified, high-value deployment contracts directly with the U.S. Department of Defence and various components of the intelligence community.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">A Radical Shift in Washington’s Procurement Strategy</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The timing of Twenty’s meteoric rise aligns perfectly with a fundamental doctrine shift within the White House and global defence institutions. Confronted by systemic, state-sponsored cyber espionage campaigns targeting Western critical infrastructure, government leadership has signalled a move toward aggressive forward defence. Current national security priorities call for the deployment of active offensive cyber operations to disrupt hostile networks and deliberately raise the economic and operational costs of aggression for foreign adversaries.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Venture capital, which historically steered clear of kinetic or offensive military software due to reputational risks and elongated government sales cycles, has rapidly adapted to this new reality. Investors are waking up to the fact that the modern defence industrial base requires agile, software-first commercial startups rather than just legacy hardware defence primes.</span></p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/twenty-raises-100m-reaches-1-billion-valuation/" data-wpel-link="internal">Twenty Raises $100M, Reaches $1 Billion Valuation</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
			</item>
