										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://www.deepseek.com/en/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">DeepSeek</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">, the AI research lab that shook up the world technology industry, announced the completion of its first round of external </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/neura-robotics-raises-record-1-4b-in-funding-round/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">financing</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">. It has successfully attracted more than 50 billion yuan (~$7.4 billion) in funds, taking its post-equity valuation above the $50 billion mark (ranging from $52 billion to $59 billion according to different reports).</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The deal is one of the largest private financings ever for artificial intelligence. It is a startling departure for a company that once boasted that it was run entirely without venture capital or any backing from an outside corporation.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Retaining Absolute Control</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">While the dollar figure is off the charts, the deal&#8217;s structural provisions have caught the attention of worldwide financial experts. </span>Founders led this deal, structuring it to shield the startup from external influence and give management a clear operational mandate.</p>
<p>The deal did not give most participants direct stakes or shareholdings, nor conventional voting rights. DeepSeek founder and CEO Liang Wenfeng solely managed an ultra-closed limited partnership structure that directed their funds.</p>
<div id="attachment_202889" style="width: 1034px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-202889" class="size-large wp-image-202889" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Deepseek-1024x683.jpg" alt="Deepseek" width="1024" height="683" /><p id="caption-attachment-202889" class="wp-caption-text">Source: Unsplash</p></div>
<p>These external investors must observe a rigid five-year capital freeze, unable to liquidate their stake or access capital markets for a quick exit. China&#8217;s state-backed National Artificial Intelligence Industry Investment Fund is the only exception to these constrictive terms. <span style="font-weight: 400">The state-backed entity secured direct equity and voting rights, formally anchoring DeepSeek&#8217;s long-term dependence on the country&#8217;s national technological framework.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/neura-robotics-raises-record-1-4b-in-funding-round/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">Neura Robotics Raises Record $1.4B in Funding Round</span></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Unconventional Backers and Internal Motivation</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The grouping of key external investors presents a stark contrast to the typical venture capital syndicates that fund Western AI research institutions. The Chinese technology giant Tencent and electric vehicle battery manufacturing behemoth CATL led the round.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Most importantly, a massive chunk of that $7.4 billion was from the founder himself. Liang Wenfeng infused about 20 billion yuan, or approximately $2.8 billion, into the fundraise himself. This self-funding part provides a greater sense of how much of the company was uniquely born. DeepSeek was first incubated within HighFlyer Capital Management, an immensely successful quantitative hedge fund set up by Liang that used black box proprietary algorithmic trading methods that created trillion-dollar capital reserves.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Sources close to the situation attribute the blow-up to demand, not a lack of computing capital, but the retention of employees. DeepSeek&#8217;s domestic competitors were in a bidding war to hire away its researchers, and the firm needed a &#8220;formalised, highly valued&#8221; equity pool to properly compensate its people using attractive stock options.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Upending Silicon Valley Economics</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">DeepSeek emerged from an unknown domestic research lab to a dominant global force with the successive launches of its V3 and R1 reasoning models. The open-weight systems produced performance capabilities comparable with the top Silicon Valley players, but they were trained on merely a tenth of the budget typically required for Western infrastructure models. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The funding round takes place after the launch of its gigantic V4 system, deployed on localised Huawei hardware. DeepSeek has capitalised on its structural cost advantages to create an aggressive price war within the wider AI environment by offering long-term price reductions on its professional developer tiers. This is a proposition that provides input and output costs of several orders of magnitude cheaper than Western alternatives, like OpenAI&#8217;s GPT-5.5.</span></p>
